lasts forever: editing books for children -- t18. Lives that matter" editing biography, autobiography and memoir -- t19. Of monographs and magnum opuses: editing works of scholarship -- t20. Reliable Sources: reference editing and publishing -- t21. The pink should be a surprise: Creating illustrated books -- tPart 5. Pursuing a publishing careen: Varieties of editorial experience -- t22. Widening the gates: why publishing needs diversity. -- t23. The apprentice: On being and editorial assistant -- t24. This pencil for hire: making a career as a freelancer editor -- t25. The self-publisher as self-editor -- t26. A new age od discovery: the editor's role in a changing publishing industry -- tConclusion. As time goes by -- tAcknowledgments -- tGlossary -- tFurther resources -- tAbout the editor -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEditing is an invisible art where the very best work goes undetected. Editors strive to create books that are enlightening, seamless, and pleasurable to read, all while giving credit to the author. This makes it all the more difficult to truly understand the range of roles they inhabit while shepherding a project from concept to publication. In What Editors Do, Peter Ginna gathers essays from twenty-seven leading figures in book publishing about their work. Representing both large houses and small, and encompassing trade, textbook, academic, and children’s publishing, the contributors make the case for why editing remains a vital function to writers—and readers—everywhere. Ironically for an industry built on words, there has been a scarcity of written guidance on how to actually approach the work of editing. This book will serve as a compendium of professional advice and will be a resource both for those entering the profession (or already in it) and for those outside publishing who seek an understanding of it. It sheds light on how editors acquire books, what constitutes a strong author-editor relationship, and the editor’s vital role at each stage of the publishing process—a role that extends far beyond marking up the author’s text. This collection treats editing as both art and craft, and also as a career. It explores how editors balance passion against the economic realities of publishing. What Editors Do shows why, in the face of a rapidly changing publishing landscape, editors are more important than ever.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEditing. 0aPublishers and publishing. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / General.2bisacsh  apublishing, editing, academic, textbooks, trade editors, acquisitions, proposal, book, literary agent, development, line, copyediting, manager, publicity, independent, fiction, genre, childrens books, nonfiction, biography, autobiography, memoir, scholarship, illustrations, reference, diversity, editorial assistant, freelance, career, self-publishing.1 aAaronson, Deb, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAdams, Katie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBritton, Gregory, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoveney, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEckstut, Arielle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerber, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedman, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGill, Diana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGinna, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGinna, Peter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGoldman, Erika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabu